  :prose
"; Wordsworth + Shelley — analysis frames

(poetry-wordsworth-shelley
  :count 4

  (reading-anchor
    :id \"wd-01-tintern\"
    :quoted-from \"Wordsworth, Lines Composed a Few Miles above Tintern Abbey, public domain\"
    :verbatim
    \"Five years have past; five summers, with the length
Of five long winters! and again I hear
These waters, rolling from their mountain-springs
With a soft inland murmur.\"
    :analysis
    \"Wordsworth returns to a specific place after five years. The
opening lines could be prose — no rhyme, no obvious meter-flourish.
What makes them poetry is what the counting does.

'Five years have past; five summers, with the length / Of five long
winters.' The number is stated three times, from three angles. This
is not padding. It is the mind measuring the duration in different
ways — the calendar count, the seasons of light, the seasons of
cold. Each of the three measurements gives the return a different
weight.

Then: 'and again I hear these waters.' The again is the whole
poem's engine. Return-after-absence is the situation. What has
changed in the speaker will be the subject.

Modern translation (the runtime's voice, analysis frame):
  'It's been five years — five summers, and five long winters. And
   here I am again, listening to the water come down from the hills.'

Word drift:
  'past' (not 'passed') = archaic spelling. Same word for us.
  'murmur' — Wordsworth's ear was tuned to water sounds. 'Murmur'
    for him carried both the water's sound and the mind's soft
    voice.

Tie back:
  Returning to a place you knew years ago is a small individuation
  practice. Who were you? Who are you now? The place has not
  changed as much as you have. Naming the change requires the
  return.\")

  (essay
    :id \"wd-02-nature-and-mind\"
    :title \"Wordsworth on nature as the mind's mirror\"
    :prose
    \"Wordsworth's central move is not description of nature. Description
of nature was already a long tradition when he arrived. His move is
naming the way the mind and nature answer each other.

In the analysis frame, this is close to what phenomenology later
called the constitutive relation between subject and world — neither
comes first, they are formed together. Wordsworth wrote this decades
before Husserl, in verse.

His famous line 'the mind of man' being 'the haunt, and the main
region of my song' says explicitly what many of his poems perform.
The subject of a Wordsworth poem is often not the mountain or the
lake but the mind's meeting with them.

This is why Wordsworth reads modern. His poems are not landscape
paintings. They are records of a mind in the act of seeing. The
mountains and lakes and waters are there — really there, not
symbolic — but they are always seen through a mind that is also
being formed by the seeing.

The daffodils poem — 'I wandered lonely as a cloud' — is the
teaching example. The daffodils are real. The speaker's memory of
them is what the poem is about. The final stanza, where the memory
returns 'upon that inward eye which is the bliss of solitude,' is
the whole point. Nature has become an inner faculty.\")

  (reading-anchor
    :id \"sh-01-ozymandias\"
    :quoted-from \"Percy Bysshe Shelley, Ozymandias, public domain\"
    :verbatim
    \"I met a traveller from an antique land
Who said: 'Two vast and trunkless legs of stone
Stand in the desert.... Near them, on the sand,
Half sunk, a shattered visage lies, whose frown,
And wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command,
Tell that its sculptor well those passions read
Which yet survive, stamped on these lifeless things,
The hand that mocked them, and the heart that fed;
And on the pedestal, these words appear:
My name is Ozymandias, King of Kings;
Look on my Works, ye Mighty, and despair!
Nothing beside remains. Round the decay
Of that colossal Wreck, boundless and bare
The lone and level sands stretch far away.'\"
    :analysis
    \"A sonnet with an unusual rhyme scheme and a clear message: the
king who built the monument for eternity is remembered only through
the ruin.

But the poem's shape is more interesting than its message.

Note the framing. The speaker did not see the ruin. The speaker met
a traveller. The traveller told him. The whole poem is inside the
traveller's quotation. The 'I' of the poem never sees Ozymandias.
This distance is important.

Note the pedestal. The king's boast is preserved verbatim. His
words survive on the stone. The words are meant to intimidate. In
the ruin, they instead confirm the king's futility.

Note the ending. 'The lone and level sands stretch far away.' Two
adjectives before the noun. Then a verb of motion. The sand is the
subject, not the king. The desert has outlasted the empire.

Modern translation (the runtime's voice, analysis frame):
  'A traveler told me about a ruin in the desert. Two stone legs, a
   broken face nearby. The face was carved so well you can still see
   the king's cruelty. On the base of the statue: My name is
   Ozymandias, King of Kings; Look on my works and despair! Nothing
   else remains. Just sand, all around, going on forever.'

Tie back:
  Ozymandias is a poem about a shop owner who thought they were
  bigger than the shape of shopkeeping. The market outlasts every
  particular market. The sand outlasts the king.\")

  (essay
    :id \"sh-02-shelley-and-idealism\"
    :title \"Shelley: the poet as legislator\"
    :prose
    \"Shelley's famous claim — 'Poets are the unacknowledged legislators
of the world' — is often quoted without its context. The context
matters.

Shelley was arguing that the imagination is the source of moral and
political change. Not the law courts. Not the parliaments. The
imagination. The claim is that when a poet writes a great poem, the
poem changes what people can imagine. What can be imagined precedes
what can be lived.

In the analysis frame, this is close to what later thinkers said
about how vocabulary determines what can be thought. Shelley put it
first in the language of poetry: the poet extends the range of what
is thinkable, and everyone downstream benefits.

The claim can sound like poet-vanity. It isn't, exactly. Shelley
knew that the effect of poetry is delayed. Poets don't legislate
directly. They shift the space of possibilities. Legislators later
occupy the shifted space.

This is why 'Ozymandias' matters even now. The image of ruined
grandeur outlasting boastful power has become a common way to
think. It is now imaginable. Two hundred years later, we talk about
Ozymandian projects. The poet's contribution was the making-visible
of a shape.

Modern operator take: the small shop that survives while big
platforms boast may be a small Ozymandias-inversion. The sand
outlasts the king. The bodega outlasts the fad.\"))
")
